Vea, liſe is sweetest before the feelings are awale, [for lacl of
feeling is a painless ill, —until one learns to lnow joy or pain.
But when thou shalt come unto that lnowledge, then must thou
see to prove among thy father's foes of hat mettle and hat
sire thou art.
Meanwhile feed on light breezes, and nurse thy tender life,
for this thy mother's joy. No fear, I wot, lest any of the Greels
assail thee with cruel outrage, even when thou hast me no more.
So trusty is the warder whom I will leave to guard thee, even
Teucer; who will not falter in his care ſor thee, albeit no he
is following a far path, busied with chase of foes.
O my warriors, seafaring comradesl On you, as on him, I
